However, there is still no 100% certainty among physicists that this is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a completely new particle that is very similar to the Higgs boson, as predicted by the standard model.
New data released this week during the big physics congress in Kyoto rather confirms it, but all the data is still missing so that we can be absolutely sure.
However, suppose it is a Higgs boson, as the risks of error appear small, and let&#39;s look at what it is.
In this world, there is a completely unquestionable law, according to which two things cannot occur at the same time in the same place.
This rule cannot be circumvented - and do not try too hard, otherwise you will get hurt.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that a similar law applies to it: Pauli&#39;s exclusion principle, according to which two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same &quot;quantum state&quot; - this &quot;state&quot; roughly speaking creates some of their properties.
It further divides physics particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find orderly citizens, or fermions, who obediently follow Pauli&#39;s principle.
And at the other end are bosons, mean, anarchists who value nothing at all - certainly not of this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the equipment (by the way, absolutely amazing) The Particle Adventure in Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons we leave unnoticed here and the &quot;force particles&quot; that propagate great natural forces and with which Higgs the boson was probably related in some way.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as might be thought.
If you read this article, it is due to the boson with an unusual banality: a photon, or &quot;particle of light&quot;, which is the &quot;carrier&quot; of electromagnetic force.
This is because when an electrically charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it &quot;disrupts&quot; the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This &quot;disturbance&quot; creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons, the &quot;carriers of force.&quot;
More stable field
It is also with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be &quot;disturbed&quot; for this boson to appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to reach very high energy values, similarly to the frozen surface of the pond, which is already rippling only a very large boulder.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge part accelerator as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - a large hadron accelerator with responsive beams is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - in order to develop such energy.
