There is no omnipotent care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who wish to die thank their attending physicians for failing to fulfill their wishes when the palliative care team relieved the pain.
But it must be said that palliative care is definitely not omnipotent in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Grand Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, patients are reluctant to treat pain in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often use palliative sedatives, which put the patient to sleep until the moment of death, either suddenly or whether the sedatives are given to him permanently.
It cannot be pretended that we do not perceive this part of suffering.
A patient who is not relieved of pain will increasingly have access to palliative sedatives.
Patients who are not given a sedative always say the same thing: &quot;I want to die.&quot;
