Thanks to 15,000 computers connected to the network, approximately 200,000 transactions have already been registered.
About a thousand websites already accept bitcoins as gifts or as a means of payment.
The bitcoin rate first peaked at $ 30 (23 euros) in June 2011, dropped to $ 2 five months later, and is now hovering around $ 10 (for a list of rates, see bitcoincharts.com).
Compared to the world&#39;s exchange for real money or financial products, this is nothing impressive.
And yet the European Central Bank (ECB) is interested in this in its report on virtual finance, which was published in October.
He describes Bitcoin as &quot;the most successful virtual money&quot;, &quot;competing with the dollar and the euro&quot; and &quot;the equivalent of ordinary money&quot;.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual money in that it is used as &quot;credits&quot; for advancing in a video game that one obtains through play or that one can buy (and sometimes exchange back).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
However, every month the central authority checks and processes individual communications.
In the case of Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are current account depositories, controllers, money issuers and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses via e-mail.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in a public account of current accounts, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key phase is to write this new transaction in this book.
It is done by solving a mathematical task assigned to computers, the solver of which, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the right to complete this additional line.
This is the stage of cutting the file; ie the transformation of a huge file into a shorter and unique digital fingerprint.
Computers &quot;take over&quot; this new transaction and add a number to it, only then &quot;chop the whole&quot;.
The goal is to find a number that provides a specific fingerprint (a lot of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes can easily check for it.
The transaction then appears indestructibly linked to a string of all other transactions; any modification would change the fingerprint.
If the user wants to pay twice with the same money for the fraud very quickly in a row (within ten minutes), the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned, because each has a different fingerprint.
The computer that solves the challenge will win 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this remuneration is regularly divided by two, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they can be divided into hundreds of millions, so there is room for margin ...
The difficulty of the assigned task also increases with increasing level of calculation.
The network has already experienced its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been compromised and stored bitcoins have been stolen.
&quot;The loophole used is not about the protocol itself,&quot; said Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real money payment company using Bitcoin.
The ECB also controls money laundering options through this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Prominent players like Wikipedia reject gifts of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed a book of current accounts and found that almost 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
&quot;Huge discounts&quot; were launched in November.
&quot;Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,&quot; rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a pedagogical book on this money, has great confidence in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payments, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, which makes them cheaper.
In addition, the bearer manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up at retailers where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
All you have to do is provide an address that can be &quot;photographed and recognized&quot; by phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement to question hierarchical systems and a shift to more horizontal systems.
&quot;It will take some time for Bitcoin to gain ground, but 2013 could be a decisive year,&quot; he predicts.
In addition, the ECB envisages in its report a reassessment of the various risks that are considered to be increased today if this type of money is successful.
