Difficult work on the Egyptian constitution
President Muhammad Mursi has embarked on another game of poker.
While Egypt remains the most divided in its history due to the promulgation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to play the bait.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of the opinion of everyone else, that the Constituent Assembly would approve the final text tomorrow.
Less than a week ago, the head of state gave the assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been using a provisional text that has been amended many times, weakening the country&#39;s constitutional stability and leading to legal speculation.
This new initiative has only further strengthened the country&#39;s rift.
From the perspective of the opposition, the president persists in his &quot;autocratic delirium,&quot; continues to &quot;break his word&quot; and &quot;trample on the law.&quot;
However, his supporters assure him that this is a means of turning the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speeding up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in two weeks.
This is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to abandon the intention of the text to explain to the Egyptians article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to regain national and democratic legitimacy while protests run throughout the country.
As confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Muhammad Mursi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favor.
Especially because this hastily organized vote puts the Egyptian people before the ultimatum: &quot;You will either approve my text or I will retain unlimited powers&quot;, which would otherwise end after the approval of the new constitution.
And in this strange atmosphere yesterday, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, approved the text.
Most liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, shortly before the promulgation of the constitution, they slammed the door stating that they could not enforce their views.
Human rights defenders, civil society or members of religious minorities have imitated their move.
In order to reach a quorum, 11 alternate members were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, the articles of the constitution were often voted on unanimously.
Commentators further commented that one of the few disputes revolved around the ... prayer hour that day, with some committee members believing that the meeting room clock was not set correctly.
The text, which was voted on last night, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains in line with the 1971 version of the Constitution, stating that &quot;the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law&quot;.
The Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental requirements, hoped to replace the term &quot;principles&quot; with the term &quot;rules&quot;, which would allow for stricter application.
For Islamists, on the other hand, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other parts of Egyptian society.
&quot;Hypocrisy,&quot; says the Liberals, who see only a rhetorical problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts al-Azhar University with an advisory role, in particular on issues related to the control of compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egyptian expert Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because &quot;those called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
This can be seen in the beginnings of theocracy &quot;.
Liberals&#39; fears are further fueled by the fact that the university&#39;s next rector should be less moderate than the current one.
&quot;So far, there has been no specific religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a broad civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulams, but university staff, many of whom have graduated from French schools, &quot;said Alexis Blouet, who is preparing to work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, he agrees that &quot;there may be inconsistencies in the interpretation of Article 220, as the terms used in it belong to a religious dictionary.
There is in particular a reference to &quot;fiqh&quot; [Islamic jurisprudence, note. ed.].
And in the future, the question may arise as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to comment on this. &quot;
Apart from the religious aspects, the text approved yesterday is highly criticized due to the extended powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that they have been significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers vested in the military.
In line with the wishes of military officials, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
Furthermore, proceedings against civilians will not be prohibited in military courts, as requested by the Association for the Protection of Human Rights.
These associations talk about their doubts in connection with the text, which they say is directed against freedom.
The crime of blasphemy is perpetuated and insult is still prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In its view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture laid down in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will then manifest on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the navel of the world and the sea from saturated salt solution await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and the integrity of nature.
AaF has identified the five most important reasons why you should visit Israel.
Bow to holy places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is claimed that God&#39;s mercy will descend on all who enter this &quot;bath.&quot;
