A shuttle bus takes tourists from the foot of the hill to this ski paradise.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods allegedly lived on top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can&#39;t visit them all in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Museum of Israel, which is located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It contains ancient Qumran manuscripts or scrolls from the Dead Sea, which were found in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as approximately 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
Impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso are widely represented in his exhibition with their canvases.
In Akkon, you can visit the Al Basha Spa Museum, which introduces visitors to several rooms of the ancient Turkish baths with mannequins of the spa users and spa nurses from that time.
In Caesarei, the unique private Ralli Museum is worth a visit, where you can admire the statues of Dali and Roden.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are strictly refused.
The Fifth Museum - the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv - tells the story of one of the most dramatic aspects of history.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children&#39;s Memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter inside - and you find yourself in complete darkness.
The stars are glittering.
And the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they perished are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improve your health
Israel&#39;s three main spas are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Seas.
Each offers swimming pools, aqua parks, a dolphinarium and an oceanarium.
It is interesting that you can swim in the Red Sea even in the winter months, because the water temperature in it does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius and the air heats up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people bathe in it all year round.
By the way, the Dead Sea is the strangest sea in the world, located at the lowest land point on the planet - at 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a saturated saline solution that easily keeps even those who cannot swim afloat.
The surrounding landscape is unrealistically beautiful.
Come here to undergo treatment using salt water - brine, and a healing mud that can cure health problems with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes to heal tangled nerves.
Touch the mysterious ancient past
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia passed through them.
Mentions of this city are found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life together.
Tourists really love wandering the narrow streets, named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you press against the walls in the alley of &quot;your&quot; sign, happiness will be favorable to you.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come here from all over Israel and even other countries to be photographed.
And in Caesarea - in the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theater and &quot;conquer&quot; the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
Today, the carefully renovated theater is used for evening concerts and opera performances.
