If the organism is not affected by the earth&#39;s gravity, it cannot properly shape the skeleton or muscle system.
It is not possible to dress a newborn in orbit as an adult in a special suit with a load in which he could train.
He will simply be deprived of what he absolutely needs to develop.
&quot;If we go with you to an experiment that allows the birth of a child in a foreign environment, we will bring to Earth a disabled person who will be completely unadapted to the local environment,&quot; predicts the head of the IBMP RAN Bioethics Commission Igor Pestov.
So the birth of children in space today is just a theoretical question.
But one day the time will come when the earthlings will set out in their ships to a distant planet, which will become the home of their descendants born in space.
SAO chief: The control of the Schwartz system failed due to politicians
In connection with public procurement, the Czechia has good controllers and quality legislation, but it lags behind in its application.
In an interview for Aktuálně.cz, Miloslav Kala, Vice President of the Supreme Audit Office, says this.
&quot;The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - that&#39;s what I think is missing in our country,&quot; Kala comments on the current situation.
Similar conclusions are also indicated by the joint inspection of Czech and German inspectors.
He cites Petr Nečas&#39;s approach to the so-called &quot;Schwartz system&quot; as an example of incorrect practice.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS will not bother entrepreneurs with its inspections - is it banned or permitted?
&quot;After all, the law must be set in some way, and if it forbids something, even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the activity of the office, which has the duty to go to control and enforce duties,&quot; states Kala.
At the meeting of the Control Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint project between the Czech and German sides, in which the legislation concerning public procurement in both countries was compared.
What exactly was it about?
This is a parallel inspection, which we started about two years ago.
To put it simply, European legislation regulates how to deal with public procurement, followed by individual national legislation and then also the practice itself.
We have put all this together, and even though the inspection has not yet been completed, we have shown very interesting differences - in general, the legislation may be &quot;stricter and more perfect&quot; in our country, but the practice itself is better in Germany in some parameters.
It is thus confirmed that it is not enough to create more and more precise rules, but it is necessary to pay attention to the application of law itself.
What can this project actually help you with, what does it mean for you?
It is precisely such joint control that could help us to stop making efforts to clarify laws, reduce and improve limits when it does not have such a positive impact.
Economy means getting the right thing for a reasonable (which does not always mean the lowest) price, in order to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal behavior.
But by lowering the order limit, we do not necessarily achieve this.
Maybe the system will be flooded with so much &quot;paper&quot; that those who want to look for holes in the system will be much easier to draw from it than if the limit remained higher.
You are talking about domestic problems with the transposition of public procurement legislation into practice.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an office similar to our SAO, or is it set up differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, just as the SAO operates there, the Bundesrechnungshof, which is organized similarly to us, also has a college, it is only formed in a slightly different way, but in principle both offices proceed similarly.
The powers are also somewhat similar, but because Germany has a federal structure, it also has these courts at the level of the individual Länder - the system is a little different from ours.
The BRH can only control federal money, represented in our country by state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by regions and municipalities in our country, are controlled there from the level of federal accounting courts.
As for the local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare it without specific data, however, in some respects Germany is described as a model, but it cannot be said that it is better in everything.
So is it also necessary that they have better controllers?
Certainly not, but again, I don&#39;t like such comparisons.
But it must be said that even the countries that we consider to be a model face a number of problems.
Otherwise, it would be of no benefit to them to cooperate with our office, would it?
As far as domestic legislation is concerned, what did the amendment to the Public Procurement Act mean to your office, are its effects already manifesting themselves?
Due to the fact that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been reflected in our inspections.
Because we do ex post checks, there is a certain delay.
So far, we are only seeing this in the process of preparing future inspections - we have launched our new tool &quot;detection of risks of inefficiency&quot;, through which we drove almost 14 thousand public contracts, and analyzed them - there will of course be reflected in changes, because the limits, conditions some types of competition will be adjusted and so on.
Do you consider the approval of this law to be more of a benefit or an additional burden on the system of bureaucracy?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction, and I hope it will be confirmed.
The problem that can arise here is that the rules will be &quot;tightened&quot; and it will not be possible to follow them.
Even during the operation of the previous rules, the inspected persons are obliged by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programs by the regional council) that any non-compliance with the Public Procurement Act constitutes a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it worthwhile to tighten the law in this way?
I don&#39;t think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse it, and not punish those who make a formal mistake that does not affect decision-making.
Such a system will only put more pressure on bureaucracy.
So how to get out of it?
Let&#39;s see where the road doesn&#39;t lead.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs by checking the so-called &quot;Schwartz system&quot; - and what does that mean?
Is the Schwartz system disabled or enabled?
After all, the law must be set in some way, and if it forbids something, even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the activity of the office, which has the duty to go to control and enforce duties.
He can say, &quot;We will change the law and allow it,&quot; but he cannot say that we will do it as nothing.
There are relatively strict rules in the Public Procurement Act as to what is to be formally done - which is right to protect public competition.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when the applicant with the best offer is excluded only for formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - this is what we believe is missing in our country.
