Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of this European Space Agency, as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began working closely with ESA in 1994 and has participated in a number of the Agency&#39;s projects over the years.
However, Poland&#39;s journey into space began much earlier.
Space enthusiasts had been flying into space before World War II; but they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, a lecture by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on 6 December 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work, Entry into Cosmonautics.
The ideas of a young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his Entry into Cosmonautics in France.
The mentioned Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and written a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-famous promoter of cosmonautics, and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railcar was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is not known and the details of the project are not known.
It is also not clear whether the rocket was to be used to launch the trolley or to brake it.
Information about this handcar is known only from the periodical press.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to deal with missiles.
The research was provided by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfek and prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the preserved materials it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, the arrival of German troops interrupted the research.
In 1937, a design of a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the trade press, and the following year the work Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza by Leliwy-Krzywoblocký was published.
Both projects were designed for the military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were dealt with by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of operation, its activities ended with the start of the war.
Other works devoted to cosmonautics appear in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, the company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the magazine Problemy, which contains four more extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, from prof. M. Subotowicz, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway, and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been seeking to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and in the autumn the PTA became a full member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the highly successful RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a range of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 missile began in the Bled Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of development was to be capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 missile was to have access to up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the altitude wind.
However, in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM missiles was the Meteor-1 missile developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 liters, the Meteor-1B 0.34 liters and the Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aviation Institute developed the Meteor-2 missile, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to withstand a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Subsequently, versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
Mention should also be made of Poland&#39;s accession to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites under the Interkosmos program, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not the answer.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
The resolution provoked a lively public discussion.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the issue from a broader perspective.
Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU, as in a globalized world, are based on the principle of more, unregulated competition.
In effect, this means that the individual economic units, the national economic systems, are in constant conflict with each other.
The reason is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
Due to significant differences in the price of labor (wages), there is a price tension.
This term is to be understood as a situation in which a manufacturer seeks to compete with low-cost goods by &quot;undermining&quot; a competitor&#39;s price in order to gain a larger share of the market and thereby increase its own profits.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either to relocate production abroad, or to buy there cheaply, or to disappear. The result is high unemployment in countries where labor prices are high compared to other economies.
Because private capital has no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it produces, the state&#39;s social spending necessarily increases.
The whole situation is exacerbated by the complete reluctance of business owners to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social societal damage he has caused in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that there is no need to provide specific statistics.
Reckless practices of private capital create a situation in individual economies, where the governments of individual countries are forced to enter into mutual competition with the aim of artificially lowering the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments give private capital a chance for its own population, regardless of the social decline.
This is reflected primarily in changes in applicable laws.
The aim is to economically force one&#39;s own population to accept the price dictate of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This is done both by a system of economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment and by restricting employees&#39; rights in the field of labor law.
The result is growing poverty, along with a widening gap between rich and poor.
For many years, there have been public food outlets in Germany for the poor who cannot make a living from their own work.
The number of these people is already in the millions.
As part of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for duly employed people to receive such a wage that the state has to pay them to the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal was also published in the case of auxiliary staff of the Federal Assembly.
Austerity measures in virtually all of the EU&#39;s southern states undoubtedly lead to the same situation where, under the pressure of a catastrophic decline in social standards, people are forced to either emigrate as they did in the 19th century or live on hungry wages on the margins of society in the hope of comes private investment capital.
But here it is necessary to ask where it will come from?
If it is from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, because a Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, or Turk, Moroccan, or Egyptian, or African is still working for a fraction of the European wage.
This applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theories and the media faint that the state cannot participate in capital on its own economy, that a controlled economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly insists that the state must not interfere with the economy through management interventions.
Then it is necessary to ask whether private capital does not affect, now it actually controls politics and thus the whole state in its own selfish sense.
Here is the clear answer that yes.
The proof is the existence of a virtually omnipotent and ubiquitous lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifested in the area of corruption, the provision of mutual benefits, legislation, where virtually everything is reprehensible, but nothing criminal.
In Germany, the situation is such that, due to a lack of funds, state ministries commission draft law to private law firms that are heavily connected with industry.
These bills are then agreed in the Bundestag.
All power thus does not come from the people, as proclaimed by Western-type constitutions, but from financially strong groups that prefer their own interests.
It is clear that liberal-oriented democracies are now rapidly entering the situation, as described by Appianus in his work The Crisis of the Roman Republic in Caesar and Pompey: &quot;The state has long been in complete disarray and the authorities have been occupied by force.
For bribes, gaining favor and using stones or swords.
Bribery and corruption flourished without any restraint and the people went to the polls with a pre-sold vote &quot;...&quot; character people did not run for office at all, so once it was due to this disruption was to stand for eight months without consuls &quot;.. ..&quot; indeed, to speak of the fact that the only cure in a bad situation is self-government and that an energetic man must be chosen. &quot;Appianes thought of Pompey, but it became Caesar who turned a permanent democracy into self-government.
Conclusion As in antiquity, today&#39;s society is based on a ruthless preference for self-interest, regardless of societal interest.
Private capital is no longer inherently able to understand and apply societal benefits.
The result is now, as then, the unprecedented decadence of elites without any effort for deeper reforms.
The causality of the rise of fascist and communist regimes must therefore be sought in the ruthless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the current situation, the demise of these systems in favor of a liberal-type democracy can be considered a break with the expectation of another round.
Particularly catastrophic is the fact that the current elites completely ignore the possible hundreds of thousands of loss of life, humanitarian and social catastrophes that we are already witnessing, along with crimes against humanity, as we know them from old and new history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least not a permanent one.
Under the pressure of competition at both the international and domestic European levels, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
