In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the US embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the overthrown Shah Mohamed Reza Pahlavi, who fled to the United States after the revolution, which had been the patron of his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer a positive way out for the American administration - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because it would fundamentally jeopardize the confidence of the Allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime, she was unable to release the hostages.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later exacerbated by the fiasco of trying to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were eventually released after 444 days, after negotiations were brokered by the Algerian government.
Their fate at home provoked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter&#39;s loss to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
Directing actor Ben Affleck&#39;s film Argo describes one episode in the history that brought America a small victory.
Just before the embassy was occupied, six employees fled it.
After difficult vicissitudes, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, helped by an extravagant cover story - they went to Canadian passports as members of the film crew, who inspected sci-fi feature films in the country.
Genre combinations
The plan, devised by &quot;exfiltration&quot; expert Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood collaboration.
In order for the legend to be credible, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of the operation have been kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck&#39;s film is a special combination of multiple genres.
On the one hand, a realistically conceived political thriller, at the same time the so-called &quot;caper movie&quot;, the story of a successful piece, a trip - an example can be a series of Danny&#39;s partners.
The film alternates moods - on the one hand, a documentary concept from Tehran (the title sequence shows iconic period photographs of events and the way in which the same situations were presented in the film - there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the light-hearted passages from Hollywood, treated with irony and a slight exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, in the corridors of the office, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
From a ridiculous actor, he became a respected director and his acting ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, after the dark crime Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller City (2010).
It is also Affleck&#39;s first film not to take place in the director&#39;s home Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that elevated the director&#39;s older films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck also shows it in Arg, where Tehran is &quot;playing&quot; Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, reconstructing real events - the introductory sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unreliability that occur when history moves somewhere.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake crew at a Tehran bazaar).
Too many events in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story told does not actually offer much in the cinematic sense of exciting scenes.
He almost quite successfully works with it, sometimes he thinks of something to reality - everything doesn&#39;t go so elegantly there (a scene in which the impending crisis at Tehran airport is averted by a phone call in America and the runway on the runway looks pretty hair-raising).
The weakness of Arga, however, is the distraction resulting from the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in the roles of Hollywood collaborators, but their characters would deserve more space and are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck&#39;s film loses a dramatic move a bit, it is a film that can be watched with a slight interest, appreciating the realization and retro style evoking the thrillers of the 70s.
But it&#39;s hard to pull down.
As a reminder of a still somewhat living history, a proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipotent and omniscient secret services are, however, will suffice.
