Controversial EU regulations include the mandatory blending of bio-ingredients into fuels, which is harmful to nature, a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers just because they contain relatively small amounts of dangerous substances, or a directive on the size of chicken cages, which made eggs more expensive this year. .
Critics in the past also faced the de facto ban on the use of the term spread butter or the exclusion of conventional light bulbs from sale.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimeters
The EU apparatus often decides under pressure from one or another trade or industrial lobby, whose demands in Brussels are usually defended by a state or a group of states (so the Czechia now enforces the demands of its banks even with a threat of a veto).
The interests of the lobby were also due to the fact that, for example, bananas of the highest quality had to reach a length of at least 14 cm in the Union and were not allowed to show &quot;anomalous curvature&quot;.
At the same time, the European Commission defended itself by merely harmonizing the existing non-uniform national standards, which complicated trade.
Despite the opposition of some countries, the EU has already softened fruit and vegetable standards, pointing out that existing directives lead to food waste.
Last year&#39;s EU regulation, which requires that inflatable balloons sold must be warned that children under the age of 8 must not inflate them without adult supervision, may also be a candidate for winning the survey.
The EU referred here to American research, according to which balloons among toys are the leading cause of death of children from suffocation.
A similar restriction now applies to children under the age of 14 when blowing into fairground spray cans.
Curious ideas are born at home
