The Bankpoplatky.com server, in cooperation with the Association of Liberal Economists Laissez Faire, nominated for the survey, in addition to some of the above-mentioned absurdities, the EU regulation on the volume of food stocks in the territory of a Member State.
The EU set maximum amounts of food stocks that could be located in the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the Union.
The Czechia then exceeded, for example, the set volumes for canned mushrooms, for which it was threatened with a large fine.
The organizers of the survey were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having a sea, and the idea of granting subsidies to apply for a subsidy.
However, these ideas did not originate in Brussels, but in Prague.
&quot;We are handicapped because we do not have the sea.
We will ask the European Union for a refund, &quot;said in the autumn of 2004 the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD).
As an argument, he stated that a lot of grain was born in our country and as a result of the so-called intervention purchases, he had to become full of warehouses, which he had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us hundreds of millions of euros for the Czechia to continue to the ports.
In the end, the European Commission met the Czech Republic by organizing a tender for the purchase of grain from countries that do not have access to the sea.
The subsidy for obtaining the subsidy was offered to the municipalities by the Ministry of Regional Development, managed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), specifically to go to the application for subsidies from Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are an exception
While regulations are easily criticized in the Member States, the EU&#39;s efforts to regulate and at the same time make the Union as a whole operate and develop more deserve recognition, according to many experts.
According to experts, a more serious problem is, for example, the drawing of EU subsidies for projects that have nothing to do with deepening European integration, but which were forced by the Member States in budgetary negotiations.
Emotions among the Czechs are also aroused by the fact that, like other EU countries, the Czech Republic must fight in Brussels for the right to a specific designation of its traditional products, and it will not always succeed in this struggle.
Although the Czechs defended the designation of Olomouc cottage cheese after a six-year struggle with the Germans and Austrians, our producers, whose tradition dates back to the 19th century, had to be renamed our producers by the Czech Republic.
Only cane distillate products can bear the name rum, not sugar beet.
In the official list of registered EU products, in the company of world-famous feta and gorgonzola cheeses, marzipan from Lübeck, Germany or Parma ham, there are already Karlovy Vary biscuits, Pohořelice and Třeboň carp and Satu Mare hops.
Pardubice gingerbread and Hořice tubes can also be proud of the EU trademark.
