Spijkenisse, a housing estate in the immediate vicinity of Rotterdam without its own job opportunities, which is not even worth a visit, holds a special record.
This municipality with 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest level of education in the whole of the Netherlands.
To address this stupid situation, a few years ago, the decision was made to contribute to general education and to build seven nicely painted reinforced concrete miniatures of fictitious bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes.
However, the success of the educational offensive was not dizzying.
And so the city councilors realized that there was only one way to become the master of statistics: we must have a library!
Winy Maas from Rotterdam&#39;s MVRDV architectural studio, a master of insanely bold bar graphs and a contractor of funny, often even cynical buildings, accepted the matter with the usual calm and appeared at a competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smirk on his face.
And while the commission still looked around in astonishment and shrugged, the cheeky Maas piled up his presents on his size and ended his activistically reasoned speech with the words &quot;Dear urban community!&quot;
So this is my proposal for the Mountain of Books in Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain was built for 30 million euros.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Mountain of Books was awarded the second place &quot;Best Library of NL 2012&quot;.
In addition, the project is nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
The small-town gray, which could not yet offer more than a postmodern pedestrian zone and the extraordinarily ugly town hall, behind whose white facade you would rather expect a dairy, is therefore richer in a little contemporary architecture.
Above all, however, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
A long way to the book
First impression: reader&#39;s eldorado under the cheese lid.
An elevator runs through the middle of the mountain massif, but you will only discover real spatial and reader passions when overcoming the topography on foot.
The glazed interior is bright and well-arranged on all sides, the burnt floor and the elegant street lanterns clearly express the atmosphere of the public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You see park benches, a dog and boys and girls playing soccer.
And books, books, books everywhere.
&quot;Normally there are bookshelves along the facade and in the middle is a large dark space, which is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal,&quot; says Winy Maas.
We built the classic spatial configuration upside down and pushed the space for the reader from the inside out.
The interior of the Mountain of Books is cleverly used: in the middle there are offices, an internet library, a chess club, an ecological center and a home technology exchange.
A special pleasure are the black bookshelves, which are once lined with walls, once with a parapet and sometimes with a stair railing.
The appearance, structure and smell are foreign.
Even sworn architects and civil engineers shake their heads at the unknown building material.
&quot;We wanted to work with recycled materials here,&quot; says Joop Trouborst, project manager at Spijkenisse, when asked by Standard magazine.
And so one day we came across a suitable agricultural waste product in a Friesian farm.
For many years, millimeter fleece of synthetic material has been used as a base for roots in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands.
It is cheap and time efficient.
The thin textile lasts one or two seasons and is then ready to be disposed of in bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in such quantities - was pressed into plates four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous and load-bearing material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like sports shoes.
After 105 steps you will reach the top.
At the end of the almost 500-meter journey, you will be rewarded in the literary café not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, but mainly about the right humidity in the mountains of literature.
Gifts for a new soul
&quot;You probably wouldn&#39;t believe it, but despite the many glass areas, this house is an ecological demonstration project,&quot; says Trouborst.
It is heated and cooled by the earth&#39;s heat.
Although the Mountain of Books stands under a glass cover, the sun shines inside only briefly, even on sunny days.
The wide glued wooden trusses, which stand perpendicular to the glazed façade, serve as shading and capture a large part of the sunlight.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
Fully automatic blinds can handle the rest.
Stefan Spermon, an initial skeptic in the IT industry, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also Cynthia Bogarde, a teacher of traditional Chinese medicine, who even calls Boekenberg the &quot;long-awaited soul&quot; of Spijkenisse.
The reason: every resident of the city was invited to the opening a few weeks ago to donate one book from his personal collection.
Optical gaps in the not yet fully equipped library, which currently numbers 70,000, were to be filled first.
The concept worked.
The shelves are completely full.
&quot;There&#39;s nothing worse than a half-empty library,&quot; says architect Winy Maas.
&quot;I think that thanks to our invitation, every inhabitant now has a certain relationship with the new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it was just for decoration.
Thus, the MVRDV succeeded in the royal discipline, which in professional jargon is called the formation of identity.
Spijkenisse wrote the history of literature.
However young and uneducated it may be.
This is ultimately the starting point for identity.
