Enrique Pena Nieto from Mexico has a difficult start
As incoming Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares for office, Will Grant of the BBC looks at the challenges he faces and the mixed expectations of his fellow citizens.
Traffic in Mexico City is currently particularly poor.
In a city that is clogged even in the best of times, steel barriers have been erected to close several key routes to the capital and cause chaos on the roads.
However, the aim was not to prevent commuters from getting to work, but to prevent protesters from accessing parliament.
On Saturday, the new President of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive a presidential sash and take over the leadership of the nation.
He faces a challenging task.
Mexico was doing well economically at the time of the resigning Felipe Calderon, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already claimed an estimated 60,000 lives in six years.
&quot;My government has a strong commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence,&quot; President Pena Nieto told US President Barack Obama at the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve this goal.
Before shaking hands with the US president, President Pena Nieta gained political experience as governor of his home state of Mexico.
Opinions on the new leader also differ in his old homeland, the populous and vast state surrounding the capital.
Straight man.
For example, in the rural town of Valle del Bravo, he is well remembered.
Citizens attribute it to the development of tourism in the resort and the construction of infrastructure.
You can now drive to the city on one of the new motorways built by Pena Nieto. These highways are a huge improvement over the leaky and bumpy roads that used to be here.
Boards with his name also hang on the wall of a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
&quot;We expect it to bring about real and lasting change,&quot; said Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a friend and political ally of President Pen Niet&#39;s party in favor of the Institutionalized Revolution (PRI) party.
We especially hope for the interesting and real changes in security and the economy that our country so desperately needs.
After an uninterrupted 81 years in power, the PRI party was pushed out by Vicent Fox.
Mr Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the Los Pinos presidential palace, much is expected of Enrique Pen Niet inside the party.
And he rejects the statement of the opposition characterizing the new president as a man without substantial content.
He is a very straightforward man, very interested in an excellent vision of the country.
He is a great statesman and above all he is a man who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, this is not the impression that many people have of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be more apparent.
Tucked under highway overpasses in many ways resembles a suburb of the capital of Mexico itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also persistent and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called in to help deal with drug gangs operating in neighborhoods, especially violence against women.
In the last two years alone, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been dumped in desolate places next to a huge landfill.
At the time of Pena Nieto&#39;s governor, more than 1,000 women were murdered in Mexico, much more than in the notoriously violent city of Ciudad Juarez, a place synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
At best, critics of Pen Niet say he failed in office to adequately address the issue of female homicides.
And in the worst case, they accuse his leadership of closing his eyes.
In a concrete house, typical of a dilapidated neighborhood, Irinea Buendia shows me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna and suppresses crying.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
