&quot;When I arrived at her house, it looked like someone had washed her body,&quot; recalls Mrs. Buendia.
There were signs of blows on it, and the posthumous stiffness had already begun.
As her mother tells the story, Mariana stares down from the picture on the wall, next to the cross, which contains a single word: &quot;Justice.&quot;
However, this is, as the family says, exactly what they were denied.
The authorities treated me as if I were an old gossip, a troublemaker, and a whimper.
They want you to just accept what they say and keep quiet.
&quot;But it can&#39;t be right with so many mistakes and omissions,&quot; he says.
The sherpa that President Pena Nieto will receive on Saturday is accompanied by a great deal of responsibility.
In the last six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crime, and the new president has promised to be his priority during his tenure.
&quot;I hope he will be the same president as the governor,&quot; said PRI Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear most.
Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, says the military prosecutor
The military prosecutor is trying to refute Bradley Manning&#39;s allegations of ill-treatment in custody.
The hearing focuses on Manning&#39;s military detention in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants the case to be dismissed on the basis of the harsh treatment of Manning in prison.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of secret documents.
The military prosecutor is trying to prove that Private Bradley Manning, who is accused of the largest leak of secret material in US history, missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he allegedly suffered in military custody.
Military Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein at the cross-examination of Private Manning at a preliminary hearing in Ft. Maede in Maryland claimed that records of Manning&#39;s weekly visits to unit officers during his nine months in custody at Quantico, Virginia, showed no allegations of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination, which took place during the defense hearing to dismiss the case against Manning on the grounds of ill-treatment during detention, which is in itself a sufficient punishment, took place the day after Manning testified that he had considered suicide in custody. .
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing thousands of secret documents while serving in Iraq.
The material was then published online on WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning was the source of her information.
At Friday&#39;s hearing, Military Prosecutor Fein and Manning went through forms filled out by officers after a meeting with Manning at Quantico Remand Prison, where he was held under high security from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Fein asked him about these forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he rated the treatment of his guards as &quot;excellent&quot; and that the overall treatment at the facility was &quot;very professional.&quot;
The forms show no complaints of ill-treatment, although Manning&#39;s officers directly asked how he was being treated, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concerns about the various issues orally and that the officers who had visited him had spoken to him about the concerns and indicated that they would address them, but did not notice the problems.
&quot;They wrote &#39;no problems&#39; (after discussing the concerns), and that didn&#39;t necessarily mean I didn&#39;t mention them,&quot; Manning said.
Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about the treatment of his person in January 2011 during a meeting with a committee assessing suicidal thoughts, which he had expressed on the form a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during the meeting, his intention was to achieve a reduction in the &quot;injury prevention&quot; regime.
The military said it had used this restrictive regime (one level under suicide surveillance) to protect it and the safety of others.
&quot;I wanted the detainees to know that I was fine and that I wanted to abolish this injury prevention regime ... so that I could enjoy an improved quality of life, as I saw it,&quot; Manning said.
Manning on Thursday testified about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transported to a detention center at the Quantico Marine Corps in July 2010.
He said he was considering suicide in Kuwait and passed out once because of the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what would happen to him and what was happening in the world around him was very depressing.
&quot;My world has shrunk only to the base of Arifjan, to that cage,&quot; Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Manning said that after arriving in Quantico, he spent most of the days (at least 21 hours, but often more than 23 hours) in a small cell without any company.
Manning said he was only allowed one mattress, a blanket, slippers, some clothes and glasses.
He said he tried to walk because sleeping or just lying around was against the rules during the day.
Manning said he always slept with the light from outside the cell in his eyes.
He said that if the guards could not see his face when he turned to the other side at night, they woke him up and had to turn back.
Manning&#39;s lawyer lodged a formal complaint about the treatment of Private Manning in January 2011.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, a military prison in April 2011.
On Friday, Judge Manning also questioned the allegations he made in Thursday&#39;s statement that, after being forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico for a night, he was also forced to stand naked in front of guards and other fellow prisoners during the morning count.
Manning said he was not allowed to cover himself with his blanket during the count.
During Judge Manning&#39;s interrogation on Friday, he said he had decided from his guards&#39; orders that he had a blanket to cover for, but admitted that no one had given him an order to postpone it.
On Thursday, Manning said he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because he had tried to show the officer that he was not dangerous.
Manning said he told the officer he could use a belt from his underwear or his booties to hurt himself, but he didn&#39;t.
Manning testified that his underwear, his booties, and his glasses had been removed from his cell that night.
His lawyer hopes that the judge will take into account his experience during his imprisonment and that in the event of his conviction in a military court, which is expected to begin early next year, he will significantly reduce his sentence.
The defense said it planned that Manning would plead guilty to lesser crimes and that he would fight other allegations because they were too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to begin this week, with the military prosecutor expected to defend the terms of custody as justified.
The Pentagon said a statement that Manning had been held in accordance with regulations regarding all detainees held with maximum security.
Allegations against Manning include aiding the enemy, illegally disclosing intelligence documents on the Internet, transmitting national security information, and stealing public property or records.
If he is charged at all points, he can be sentenced to life imprisonment.
