Old battles, the new Middle East
A ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could still be an uncertain basis for peace.
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The next round of bloodshed suggests that not every such thing is in vain.
Among the usual unnecessary speculation about who started it, many buildings were demolished, killing more than 140 Palestinians, mostly civilians, and six Israelis. And for the first time, rockets hit Gaza near Tel Aviv, the Israeli capital, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But while Israelis and Palestinians appear to be stuck in their long-standing conflict, the Middle East is changing all around them.
The Arab Spring has changed the old order, and Palestinians and Israelis, whether they like it or not, are caught in the chaos in the region.
Maybe it will make their fight even bloodier than ever.
However, there are reasons to think that this can break their deadly stalemate.
A war that is neither won nor lost.
At first glance, there do not seem to be much reason for optimism at the moment.
Even if the ceasefire on November 21 lasted, the fighting from this week intensified the hawks on both sides.
Leaders of Hamas, the Islamic movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced Israelis to retreat, even though Gaza has been defeated.
Despite the killing of several Hamas leaders and the closure of Gaza&#39;s 1.7 million people in one of the most deplorable and populous corners of the planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining influence in the West Bank, another piece of Palestine that is currently ruled by its staunch rivals from Fatah, a more moderate Palestinian faction.
In addition, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is on their side.
Islamists have gained more influence throughout the Arab world, so Hamas has made powerful and wealthy friends.
Turkey, a resurrected regional power that was once Israel&#39;s closest Muslim ally, has joined Hamas. So is Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic countries in the Gulf.
Cheers from Hamas say the Islamic crescent is encircling Israel, in the north of Lebanon, where the Hezbollah party / militia rules, through Syria, where rebels who are increasingly leaning towards Islamism can oust Bashar Assad to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And above all, on the southern wing of Israel, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Mursi in Egypt, by far the most populous and pivotal Arab country, changed the balance in the region.
Husni Mubarak, a secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had no time for Hamas.
On the contrary, the Brotherhood is a cousin of Hamas and its leaders are more influenced by public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas may emerge as a player who cannot be ruled out by Israel or America.
By contrast, Israeli hardliners come to the opposite conclusion.
In military terminology, Hamas was put back in a box.
Israel&#39;s Iron Dome anti-missile system has proved its worth, and many Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
Israelis can sleep better - for a while.
In diplomatic terminology, America is as steadfast as ever. Many European countries have also blamed Hamas for launching the latest round of violence.
And most importantly - Israel prospered, especially under the leadership of Benjamin Netanyahu, the prime minister, who mostly ignored the peace process.
Although Gaza rockets have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, there has been relatively calm in Israel from suicide bombers, thanks in part to a wall that extends into the West Bank, a major part of what may one day be a Palestinian state, and protects Jewish settlements. which are still growing despite their illegality under international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party had teamed up with an even more radical group led by Avigdor Lieberman at the start of the January 22 election campaign, is in a good position.
Why pamper those treacherous Palestinians by giving them their own state?
If they really ruled the West Bank, wouldn&#39;t they launch rockets like their compatriots in Gaza did?
It will be better if we hold them behind that wall and hit them when they stick their heads out.
