But some scientists and child development experts are increasingly coming to praise for boredom.
They say that it is good for us (and our children) to get bored at times.
It forces the brain to go in interesting directions, which can encourage creativity.
And since most of us are constantly connected to a screen these days, we don&#39;t have a chance to enjoy boredom.
So should we encourage boredom?
Yes.
And no.
But I&#39;ll come back to that.
First, like many people, I assumed that boredom was a relatively new phenomenon that occurred with the advent of more free time.
But as Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011).
&quot;In fact, boredom has a long history,&quot; he said.
On the walls of Pompeii was found a Latin inscription about boredom, dating from the first century AD.
And then there is the question of how we define boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After reviewing the research literature and demonstrating the idea to a target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience &quot;I wanted to do something that would satisfy me, but I was not able to.&quot;
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
He says that there is no urge to do something about apathy.
He says the core of boredom is &quot;disrupting the process of attention associated with a bad mood and a feeling of slow passing time.&quot;
Boredom can be very reminiscent of depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they may have a relationship, bored people tend to see the problem as the environment or the world, while people who are depressed see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we are bored when we only have difficulty concentrating.
In their study &quot;The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention&quot;, published in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science in September, Professor Eastwood and colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape on which a person read an article from magazine.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated television program in the next room, others heard it so quietly that they barely noticed it, while the third group did not hear it at all.
Those who heard the television program quietly reported more boredom than the other two groups - they had difficulty concentrating, but they were not sure why and attributed these difficulties to boredom.
When you try to focus on a difficult or engaging task, distractions can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when you&#39;re doing something boring, &quot;like looking for the wrong parts on a factory line, distracting music can help keep you from getting bored.&quot;
In fact, he said, we now know that twisting and scribbling, often seen as a sign of boredom, can actually help fight boredom and keep people more physically alert.
&quot;Research shows that children who are allowed to fidget learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still,&quot; said Professor Fenske.
We&#39;ve all been bored at times - the delay of my flight, the humming speaker, a particularly lengthy movie.
But some individuals have a better chance of getting bored than others.
To help measure boredom, researchers developed the &quot;Boredom Proneness Scale&quot; in the 1980s.
The scale includes questions like, &quot;Many things I have to do are repeated and are monotonous,&quot; and &quot;I have so many interests that I don&#39;t have time to do them all.&quot;
Using these scales, the researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need for more and different external stimuli.
However, teenagers are generally indifferent.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored at school and doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they were not at school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know if the percentage of boredom would be higher or lower now, 21 years later.
But he said he knew that &quot;adolescence is the peak time for boredom&quot;, which is largely due to the fact that children and young people are not given much control over what they want to do.
