The hardest craft in the world: sulfur carriers in the area of Kawah Ijen volcano
For four euros, carriers in the Indonesian volcano area gamble with their lives and health as they carry 70 kilos of sulfur down steep stone paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anta Wijayi, one of the 400 miners who make a living by extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, they have to fare every day to the bottom of the crater, where sulfur gases escape from the interior of the Earth and, when in contact with air, become solid.
After cutting large blocks of sulfur, which together weigh up to 70 kilos, he takes them on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises 2,386 meters, but it takes over 40 minutes for exhausted porters to ascend at a turtle&#39;s pace, as they maintain their balance and carefully consider their steps so as not to slip and fall into the abyss.
They know that any trip could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell from the rocks of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn five cents for every kilo of sulfur they extract
When they are upstairs, they make their way past tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in a circus, and wearily carry heavy baskets to the weight that the mining company placed a little lower, at an altitude of 1850 meters.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been mining in the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupees (five cents) per kilogram of sulfur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral has a place in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even sugar bleach.
&quot;Because they normally carry 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip,&quot; explains Anto, who usually completes three trips a day.
One trip takes him three hours and in the end he is destroyed, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) a day.
While this may seem like a negligible amount for such inhuman efforts, it is three times what he would earn in the field.
&quot;The daily wage of miners is very high here. For example, coffee is paid 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and a fortnight&#39;s pay is two million rupees (167 euros),&quot; explains a carrier who previously worked on a tourist island Bali as a bricklayer.
There was a salary of 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as convincing in Indonesia as sulfur: &quot;He married I was with a young girl from Bali who is Hindu and I took her to Java to convert to Islam. &quot;
Anto has asthma, he has difficulty breathing, he still coughs and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto risks life three times a day in the Kawah Ijen volcano, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll on him, even though his face is protected by a special mask and goggles.
He has asthma, he has difficulty breathing, he still coughs and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases escaping from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
&quot;I will work for another two years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French,&quot; he promises more than good English.
This sympathetic and intelligent young man with a destiny could be a tourist guide, a waiter or a receptionist at a hotel, and instead works as a porter.
She shares a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and gets up at two o&#39;clock in the morning every day, because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night and its characteristic yellow color changes to blue and glows in the dark.
Despite the surrounding darkness, Anto digs into the crater and illuminates the path with a small flashlight, which he has attached to his helmet, and he bought it for his own money.
About 400 carriers carry baskets of sulfur from the bottom of the crater on their shoulders
Although the company has high incomes, it has not mechanized the production of sulfur due to cost savings, nor does it provide any equipment to carriers working on their own and with such effort.
In fact, they do not even receive a share of 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) from the photography surcharge, which, together with a ticket for 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), is collected by nature park guards from tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human resources. muly.
&quot;This job is for cattle, not humans,&quot; said Madrusin, a stout 42-year-old porter who has worked at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He manages to lift up to 110 kilos and assures us that he will last to work &quot;as long as he can&quot; because he needs money to educate his three sons between the ages of 18 and 10.
I&#39;m not retiring, I&#39;m going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes when the wind unexpectedly turns and catches the miners in the thick fumes that emanate from the volcano, the miners are so hard that none of them complain that they are suffering from serious diseases ... but it is clear from their frequent respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, knee pain and shoulder wounds caused by the weight of the baskets.
Unainik, who balances his basket on his back, can load only 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Every day, he and his colleagues mine 15 tons of sulfur in the volcano, which three trucks take on a steep path between the thickets to a warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
&quot;I&#39;m not retiring, I&#39;m going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life,&quot; Unainik declares, opening his mouth wide and missing a few teeth.
Of his five sons, the eldest, thirty, also earns his living by mining sulfur.
Time passes, but the constant misery of one of the most difficult crafts in the world persists from generation to generation - the crafts performed by human mules in Kawah Iljen.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans are tempted not to have children for career, stress and the cost of living and education.
&quot;Singapore&#39;s population needs growth.&quot;
I&#39;m married and I&#39;m a patriot, you&#39;re my wife and you&#39;re a patriot. Let us fulfill our civic duty and give birth to a new life!
