However, he admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously limited when they wanted to offer too many small houses in one project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
Although these new rules could lead to an increase in the nation&#39;s birth rate, an interview with Singaporeans working in the financial district in the city center suggests that they will not have much effect.
&quot;People are still stressed, houses are expensive, as is education, which is why many people put it off,&quot; says the young official.
&quot;Let the others have children.
But it&#39;s important for me to rely on my own money and time, &quot;says another young man in his early twenties.
Both men and women cite careers, stress and the cost of living and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
