What is private offline is private and online
Privacy.
According to a dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, this is something of a personal nature or &quot;an area of private life which everyone has the right to protect against any disturbance&quot;.
What is privacy for a person under 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers to which he is exposed when he publishes matters on the Internet that he would certainly not tell anyone in ordinary communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15, who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the notion of privacy to be &quot;something entirely personal&quot; on a personal level and to be a &quot;username and password&quot; when it came to social networks.
&quot;My biggest secret I wouldn&#39;t reveal,&quot; says 10-year-old Jorge, trying to explain the importance of privacy in places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
&quot;They are very secret secrets, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world,&quot; he claims.
&quot;I put nice photos or photos of how we play on FB.
I also talk to friends there.
I wouldn&#39;t share a photo that wasn&#39;t mine, or a photo that would make fun of someone, &quot;he says.
This boy realizes that it is wrong to post obscene photos, photos of naked people or photos of crimes, or to write degrading or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most are relatives.
Among them is a mother who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
&quot;I set up a Twitter account so I can express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don&#39;t know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there, &quot;he adds.
&quot;Social networking is fun, I can talk to relatives who are far or fast to communicate with friends,&quot; he says.
He does not hesitate to say that he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
He wouldn&#39;t even care if someone recommended someone unknown to him.
The case of fourteen-year-old José is different.
This teenager owns accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and admits to the last mentioned network that he does not know 20 people from his friends list.
&quot;I&#39;m not afraid of that because we have something in common, like music,&quot; he says.
According to the boy, none of them guided him to anything, nor did he want an address or a telephone number from him.
&quot;If they urge me or ask me to do so, I will simply remove them from my account,&quot; he admits.
José signed up for Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
This boy is no stranger to what is now called cyberbullying.
&quot;They blackmailed a friend on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never knew who it was, &quot;he confirms.
According to José, the victim did not log out of the account.
&quot;She just activated private mode.&quot;
It then explains a series of steps on how to set up your account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post photos of acquaintances in unpleasant or embarrassing situations.
&quot;Of course I would do it if someone bothered me or I just wanted to.
Even though I know it&#39;s cyberbullying, &quot;he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porrasová, an English teacher and a graduate of Education and Teaching, believes that in order for children and adolescents to find their way around social networks, they must understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform.
He states: &quot;The Internet was created as a means of finding information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed.&quot;
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a graduate of Yale University&#39;s pedagogy and author of Digital Natives and Digital Immigrants, introduced these concepts to explain the phenomenon.
&quot;Digital natives are children and young people who were born at the time of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, and we are still learning for ourselves, &quot;he says.
He explains that it is a complex topic, &quot;because we ask them to recognize what is appropriate to disseminate, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet mature&quot;.
Also, to be - in terms of the environment - prudent, at a time when what they desire most is to be popular, to have thousands of friends and not to think about the consequences, &quot;he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and teenagers what privacy is is to ask questions that make them think.
&quot;Telling them not to do something doesn&#39;t work,&quot; he adds.
Next, Marrielos Porras lists some of the possibilities: There are things you wouldn&#39;t tell a stranger, so why are you doing this on the Internet?
Or: Would you like someone to post your photo the way you posted your friend?
Do you know what others publish about you?
When you tag the people in the party photos, did you ask their permission?
And one more thing: Does everyone constantly need to know what you&#39;re doing?
Another point is to realize that they must behave in the Internet environment as well as outside it.
These are the same rules.
&quot;One follows the Internet from respect, morality and other principles, and the same should be true on social networks,&quot; he claims.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher and educational counselor, explains that it is essential that children&#39;s parents read the rules of social networks carefully.
&quot;If they understand all the tricks, they have a good basis for talking to children about the consequences of setting up an account on the Internet.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to be shared or published, &quot;he says.
The Guardia believes that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of &quot;do not talk to strangers&quot;.
