The ruling, approved by the United States Court of Appeals, which does not recognize Grupo Vitro&#39;s debt restructuring imposed by bankruptcy in Mexico, sets an unfortunate precedent for any national company with branches in a neighboring country and a solvency problem.
Thus, the procedures for restructuring companies allowed by Mexican law do not seem to apply in the land of stripes and stars, despite international agreements.
The approval of Judgment Harlin Hall at the North Texas Bankruptcy Court on June 15 last year leaves Mexican companies in practice unprotected against the possibility of confiscating their assets on the other side of the El Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door to a major Mexican glass manufacturer to the United States Supreme Court, appealing against three irregularities.
It should be noted at the outset that while the judge in this case claims that creditors should be governed by United States insolvency law, the New Orleans-based Fifth District Court of Appeal says the main procedure is bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico.
First, it would indicate ignorance of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinational companies.
In essence, a United Nations model law for the unification of international trade law was created for this purpose, which is appointed by the American Law Institute as an arbitrator.
Second, the judgment states that without the voting of the branches of the internal corporate structure, in which the indebtedness of the parent company Vitro to the branches is recognized, the required majority to approve the restructuring would not have been reached.
However, Mexican law allows this possibility.
The fact is that the Vitro case was not the first in which this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, such as Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose internal debts were guaranteed by the Federal Bankruptcy Institute.
In addition, it is true that even after deducting the branch votes, the creditors - who were suing Vitro in the United States, ie vulture funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited - would not reach a majority.
In the vote, they would reach about 45 percent to 37.
This information is not taken into account by the court of appeal.
From another point of view, the court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 - against the background of the serious economic crisis that has hit the United States.
Meanwhile, González Sady&#39;s family business appeals to the reassessment directly before the Court of Appeal, so that the assessment takes place in full, with the participation of five judges, as originally only three voted.
If he fails here, he will seek a review of the process by a higher instance, in this case the United States Supreme Court.
What is serious in the case is that the court omitted a document sent by the Mexican government as an amicus curiae department detailing Vitro&#39;s conduct under the Bankruptcy Act and pointing out that the company had made it easier by adhering to the agreements signed both countries to confront the law with Chapter 15 of the United States Insolvency Act.
In addition, it points out that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, namely the rules governing international insolvency cases, which guarantee equality for both debtors and creditors.
Impact on both sides: punishment for Vitro and the state.
